name: Wild Mountain Thyme
comments: Scottish/Irish folk song, also known as "Purple Heather" and "Will Ye Go, Lassie, Go?". The lyrics and melody are a variant of the song " The Braes of Balquhither " by Scottish poet Robert Tannahill (1774–1810) and Scottish composer Robert Archibald Smith (1780–1829), but were adapted by Belfast musician Francis McPeake (1885–1971) into "Wild Mountain Thyme" and first recorded by his family in 1955. The original version of the song, published in 1955, closely paraphrases the Tannahill version, which was published posthumously in 1821. Tannahill's original lyrics include a number of phrases that McPeake carried over into his song, including the lines "Let us go, lassie, go" and "And the wild mountain thyme" as he rewrote the song.

name: Since I Laid My Burden Down
comments: aka "When I Lay My Burden (s) Down" or "Glory, Glory, Hallelujah". Gospel song, typically sung at funerals. The tune is related to that of Will the Circle Be Unbroken , while the lyrics share some similarities with other spirituals and gospel songs. The song has many lyrical variations but is mostly just a recurring refrain of - Glory glory, hallelujah Since I laid my burden down (or When I laid my burdens down) Glory glory, hallelujah Since I laid my burden down (or When I laid my heavy burdens down)

comments: Justin Hayward wrote the song originally intending to name it "Tuesday Afternoon". At the insistence of producer Tony Clarke, it was named "Forever Afternoon (Tuesday?)" for its initial release on the Days of Future Passed album. However, when it was released as a single the following year, its name was changed back to "Tuesday Afternoon" and it has been more commonly known by this name ever since. Some of the Moody Blues compilation and live albums list the song as "Tuesday Afternoon (Forever Afternoon)" to reflect both titles.

Columbus Stockade Blues
comments: The historical plaque at the Columbus Stockade in Georgia reads as follows: "COLUMBUS STOCKADE BLUES" "Way Down in Columbus, Georgia, Wanna be back in Tennessee. Way down in Columbus Stockade. Friends have turned their backs on me." "The "Columbus Stockade Blues" by Thomas Darby and Jimmie Tarlton, was written and recorded in 1927. Many famous artists have since played the song in band, jazz, blue grass, country and blues arrangements. These two brick buildings served as jail and police headquarters from the 1850s to 1906. Then the buildings were joined and appear today much as they did when the song was written. The property was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1980." Frequently, artists attempt to take credit for writing old songs that were, in fact, written by others or come from a traditional source. The most notable example for this song was by Jimmie Davis and Eva Sargent who copyrighted "Columbus Stockade Blues" in 1943, more than 15 years after Thomas Darby and Jimmie Tarlton recorded it.

name: I'm Sitting on Top of the World
comments: The Henderson/Young/Lewis song "I'm Sitting on Top of the World" is a more big band era-type song that starts off "I'm sitting on top of the world, I'm rolling along....." NOTE: There is another Sitting on Top of the World by Walter Vinson that is more bluesy (or bluegrass) and starts out either "And now she’s gone but I don’t worry, ‘Cause I’m sitting on top of the world" or "It was in the spring one sunny day, My good gal left me Lord she went away". Many of the Vinson songs are mistakenly credited to Henderson/Young/Lewis.  Bill Monroe's 1957 recording erroneously credited Henderson/Young/Lewis, and now most of the bluegrass versions follow suit - but they have no lyrical or musical relation to the Henderson work. I'm sitting on top of the world, I'm rolling along, I'm rolling along. I'm quitting the blues of the world, Just singing a song, Just singing a song. Glory hallelujah, i just phoned the parson, Hey, par, get ready to call.' Just like humpty dumpty, I'm going to fall.

name: Souviens-toi de m'oublier
comments: Originally written to be included in the album Amour, année zéro . Chamfort didn't like Gainsbourg's lyrics, which he reportedly deemed "too easy", and asked Duvall to re-write them. Gainsbourg, in turn, set his lyrics to a different tune and gave the new song to Catherine Deneuve .
